Add Formspree Formbutton to a Gatsby site

I had the same issue where just typing into my JS project would cause my CPU use to skyrocket to 100% and when I stopped typing it would settle down at 12%. This was infuriating because it would cause everything else to hang, including the video player on Udemy. So I decided to apply all the advice I found in this thread to my own issue but the issue still persisted. So I decided to disable my extensions one by one to see if that solved the issue. Funnily enough, it was GitHub's own "GitHub Pull Requests and Issues" extension that caused my issue. Disabling it dropped my CPU usage from 100% to around 40%, which was a start! As another user mentioned, try disabling your extensions methodically to see if that alleviates the issue.
Error: bcrypt_lib.node is not a valid Win32 application

I faced the same issue; I installed bcrypt using the WSL subsystem with npm i bcrypt which I assume installs an architecturally specific version which doesn't mesh with Windows. I had nodemon running on my local machine's terminal and when I tried running my app, it kept crashing. So I deleted the node_modules folder and then used npm i on my local machine's terminal instead to install the packages and it worked without a hitch! (I have nodemon on my local machine because supposedly mongod doesn't work well with WSL)
Python list is not preserving order after asyncio operation

I'm currently using Python to try and develop an application using LangChain that would be able to scrape a document and put each line into a row of a table/dataframe. Then I would be calling an LLM to cross-reference the value in the row against a vectorstore to check whether there is a relationship or not. Since there can be hundreds of rows in the resulting dataframe I tried to implement asyncio to run the process concurrently (reference)), this is the code I have right now: @retry(wait=wait_random_exponential(min=1, max=60), stop=stop_after_attempt(6)) async def async_generate(chain, query, line, reply_list): (23 more lines were trimmed) But I'm running into an issue where the response are not maintaing the order of the rows in the dataframe, and the first iteration of the async_generate for the reply_list return function yields: ['', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Comply'] and the last iteration yields: ['', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Comply', 'Noted', 'Comply', 'Noted', 'Comply', 'Not applicable for current submission.', 'By Contractor', 'Not applicable for current submission.', 'Noted', 'Noted', 'Noted', 'Not applicable for current submission.', 'Not applicable for current submission'] The ideal result for the reply_list should look like this: ['', '', '', 'Comply', '', 'Not applicable for current submission', 'Comply', 'Not applicable for current submission', '', 'By Contractor', 'By Contractor', '', 'Not applicable for current submission', 'Comply', 'Comply', 'Comply', '', 'Noted', 'By Contractor', 'Noted'] It appears that whichever rows that don't meet the conditional are immediately run and appended at the beginning of the list. Is there a remedy to ensure that the async function returns values that correspond to the original row? Or is there a better implementation that I might have overlooked?
